CCOONNFFIIGGUURRAATTIIOONN FFIILLEESS
       The ggrrooffffeerr program can be preconfigured by two configuration files.

       //eettcc//ggrrooffff//ggrrooffffeerr..ccoonnff
              System-wide configuration file for ggrrooffffeerr.

       $$HHOOMMEE//..ggrrooffff//ggrrooffffeerr..ccoonnff
              User-specific  configuration  file  for  ggrrooffffeerr,  where   _$_H_O_M_E
              denotes  the  user's  home directory.  This file is called after
              the system-wide configuration file to enable overriding  by  the
              user.

       Both  files  are  handled  for the configuration, but the configuration
       file in //eettcc comes first; it is overwritten by the  configuration  file
       in  the home directory; both configuration files are overwritten by the
       environment variable _G_R_O_F_F_E_R___O_P_T; everything is overwritten by the com-
       mand line arguments.

       The  configuration  files  contain  options  that  should  be called as
       default for every ggrrooffffeerr run.  These options are written in lines such
       that  each  contains  either  a long option, a short option, or a short
       option cluster; each with or without an argument.  So  each  line  with
       configuration  information  starts  with  a minus character "--"; a line
       with a long option starts with two minus characters "----", a line with a
       short option or short option cluster starts with a single minus "--".

       The  option  names  in  the configuration files may not be abbreviated,
       they must be exact.

       The argument for a long option can be separated from  the  option  name
       either by an equal sign "==" or by whitespace, i.e. one or several space
       or tab characters.  An argument for a  short  option  or  short  option
       cluster  can  be  directly  appended to the option name or separated by
       whitespace.  The end of an argument is the end of the line.  It is  not
       allowed  to use a shell environment variable in an option name or argu-
       ment.

       It is not necessary to use quotes in an option or argument, except  for
       empty arguments.  An empty argument can be provided by appending a pair
       of quotes to the separating equal sign  or  whitespace;  with  a  short
       option, the separator can be omitted as well.  For a long option with a
       separating equal sign "==", the pair of quotes can be omitted, thus end-
       ing  the  line with the separating equal sign.  All other quote charac-
       ters are cancelled internally.

       In the configuration files, arbitrary  whitespace  is  allowed  at  the
       beginning  of  each line, it is just ignored.  Each whitespace within a
       line is replaced by a single space character " " internally.

       All lines of the configuration lines that do not  start  with  a  minus
       character  are ignored, such that comments starting with "##" are possi-
       ble.  So there are no shell commands in the configuration files.

       As an example, consider the following configuration file  that  can  be
       used either in //eettcc//ggrrooffff//ggrrooffffeerr..ccoonnff or ~~//..ggrrooffff//ggrrooffffeerr..ccoonnff ..

       # groffer configuration file
       #
       # groffer options that are used in each call of groffer
       --foreground=DarkBlue
       --resolution=100
       --viewer=gxditview -geometry 900x1200

       The  lines  starting  with  ##  are just ignored, so they act as command
       lines.  This configuration sets four ggrrooffffeerr options (the lines  start-
       ing with "--").  This has the following effects:

       * Use  a  text color of DDaarrkkBBlluuee in all viewers that support this, such
         as ggxxddiittvviieeww.

       * Use a resolution of 110000ddppii in all viewers that support this, such  as
         ggxxddiittvviieeww.  By this, the default device in _x _m_o_d_e is set to XX110000.

       * Force ggxxddiittvviieeww(1) as the _x_-_m_o_d_e viewer using the geometry option for
         setting the width to 990000ppxx and the height to 11220000ppxx.   This  geometry
         is suitable for a resolution of 110000ddppii.

       * Use xxppddff(1) as the _p_d_f_-_m_o_d_e viewer with the argument --ZZ 115500.

EEXXAAMMPPLLEESS
       The  usage  of ggrrooffffeerr is very easy.  Usually, it is just called with a
       file name or _m_a_n _p_a_g_e.  The  following  examples,  however,  show  that
       ggrrooffffeerr has much more fancy capabilities.

       _s_h_# groffer /usr/local/share/doc/groff/meintro.ms.gz

       Decompress, format and display the compressed file mmeeiinnttrroo..mmss..ggzz in the
       directory  //uussrr//llooccaall//sshhaarree//ddoocc//ggrrooffff,  using   the   standard   viewer
       ggxxddiittvviieeww  as  graphical  viewer  when  in  the X Window System, or the
       lleessss(1) pager program otherwise.

       _s_h_# groffer groff

       If the file ..//ggrrooffff exists use it as input.   Otherwise  interpret  the
       argument  as a search for the _m_a_n _p_a_g_e named ggrrooffff in the smallest pos-
       sible _m_a_n _s_e_c_t_i_o_n, being section 1 in this case.

       _s_h_# groffer man:groff

       search for the _m_a_n _p_a_g_e of ggrrooffff even when the file ..//ggrrooffff exists.

       _s_h_# groffer groff.7
       _s_h_# groffer 7 groff

       search the _m_a_n _p_a_g_e of ggrrooffff in _m_a_n _s_e_c_t_i_o_n  77.   This  section  search
       works only for a digit or a single character from a small set.

       _s_h_# groffer fb.modes

       If  the  file  ..//ffbb..mmooddeess does not exist interpret this as a search for
       the _m_a_n _p_a_g_e of ffbb..mmooddeess.  As the extension _m_o_d_e_s is not a single char-
       acter  in classical section style the argument is not split to a search
       for ffbb.

       _s_h_# groffer groff 'troff(1)' man:roff

       The arguments that are not existing files are looked-up as the  follow-
       ing  _m_a_n  _p_a_g_e_s:  ggrrooffff  (automatic search, should be found in _m_a_n sec-
       tion 1), ttrrooffff (in section 1), and rrooffff (in the section with the lowest
       number, being 7 in this case).  The quotes around _'_t_r_o_f_f_(_1_)_' are neces-
       sary because the parentheses are  special  shell  characters;  escaping
       them  with a backslash character _\_( and _\_) would be possible, too.  The
       formatted files are concatenated and displayed in one piece.

       _s_h_# LANG=de groffer --man --viewer=galeon ls

       Retrieve the German _m_a_n _p_a_g_e (language _d_e) for the llss  program,  decom-
       press it, format it to _h_t_m_l or _x_h_t_m_l format (_w_w_w _m_o_d_e) and view the re-
       sult in the web browser ggaalleeoonn.  The option ----mmaann guarantees  that  the
       _m_a_n  _p_a_g_e  is retrieved, even when a local file llss exists in the actual
       directory.

       _s_h_# groffer --source 'man:roff(7)'

       Get the _m_a_n _p_a_g_e called _r_o_f_f in _m_a_n section 7, decompress it, and print
       its unformatted content, its source code.

       _s_h_# groffer --de-p --in --ap

       This is a set of abbreviated arguments, it is determined as

       _s_h_# groffer --debug-params --intermediate-output --apropos


       _s_h_# cat file.gz | groffer -Z -mfoo

       The  file  ffiillee..ggzz is sent to standard input, this is decompressed, and
       then this is transported to the _g_r_o_f_f _i_n_t_e_r_m_e_d_i_a_t_e _o_u_t_p_u_t _m_o_d_e  without
       post-processing  (ggrrooffff  option  --ZZ),  using  macro  package _f_o_o (ggrrooffff
       option --mm).

